    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Memory leaks can be a real challenge, especially when working with large datasets. It's possible that the issue is related to the way you're handling the data, perhaps due to a circular reference or an uncollectable object. You might want to try using a garbage collector to see if it makes a difference, or use a library like `memory_profiler` to get a better understanding of your code's memory usage. \n\nHowever, I'm not surprised you're using context managers - that's a great way to ensure resources are released properly. It's still possible that there's a subtle issue lurking in the background, perhaps related to the way you're creating or modifying the data. \n\nOne thing you could try is to add some debug logging to see if the memory leak is occurring at a specific point in your code. This might help you pinpoint the source of the issue. \n\nYou know, I've seen this kind of thing before, and it's often related to the way the data is being stored or referenced. It's a bit like a hidden trapdoor in the code, leading to a memory leak that's hard to detect. But don't worry, with a bit of persistence and detective work, you should be able to track it",
      "source": "target",
